    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Right, I get the threshold part, but it feels like the \"random chance\" part is the real headache. When I'm looking at my data, there's just so much noise/variance in the samples that it's hard to tell if the result is a real trend or just statistical noise. How do you actually distinguish between a true underlying effect and just random noise in a way that's mathematically sound?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The mathematical distinction lies in the variability relative to the effect size, often quantified by standard error. If the noise (variance) is very high compared to the signal (effect), the p-value increases because the variance inflates the standard error of the estimate. To properly distinguish them, you should report and interpret effect sizes alongside p-values, as these metrics give you a measure of the magnitude of the effect independent of strict significance levels.",
      "source": "target",
