      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, when the noise is so erratic that the underlying signal is difficult to track, it is precisely what we describe as high variance or low precision in the estimates. In extreme cases, this randomness can lead to non-normal distributions or sampling instability that traditional p-value calculations may struggle with. Researchers sometimes address this by increasing sample size, which effectively reduces the standard error and dampens the influence of random noise.",
      "source": "target",
